import math
def train(X, y):
    classes = {}
    for xi, yi in zip(X, y): classes.setdefault(yi, []).append(xi)
    return {c: [sum(col)/len(pts) for col in zip(*pts)] for c, pts in classes.items()}
def predict(centroids, x):
    dist = lambda a,b: sum((p-q)**2 for p,q in zip(a,b))
    return min(centroids, key=lambda c: dist(centroids[c], x))

X=[[1,1],[1,2],[8,8],[9,8]]; y=[0,0,1,1]
c=train(X,y)
acc=sum(predict(c,xi)==yi for xi,yi in zip(X,y))/len(y)
print(acc)   # 1.0 vs random baseline 0.5
```

The model 'learned' two centroids and beats the 50% random baseline. Always compare to a trivial baseline (random, or always-predict-majority) — a model that can't beat it has learned nothing, no matter how fancy.
